---
import Post from '../../layouts/Post.astro';
const meta = {
  title: 'How I Stopped Fooling Myself With Backtests',
  deck: 'Two statistical gates — the Deflated Sharpe Ratio and the Probability of Backtest Overfitting — decide whether an alpha ever touches real money.',
  date: '2026-07-18',
  readtime: '7 min',
  project: 'Alpha Engine',
  tags: ['quant', 'overfitting', 'statistics'],
};
const body = `
<p class="lead">A backtest is a machine for generating self-flattery. You try a few dozen
variations of an idea, keep the one with the prettiest equity curve, and your brain quietly
files the result under <em>skill</em>. On a cash account that mistake costs you some tuition.
On a <strong>leveraged</strong> account — mine runs commodity CFDs on €150 of starting capital
under ESMA retail rules, with overnight financing near 7.3% annualized eating any long carry —
a spuriously high Sharpe isn&rsquo;t a curiosity. It&rsquo;s a countdown to a margin call.</p>

<p>So before any signal in my alpha engine is allowed to size a real position, it clears two
gates borrowed from L&oacute;pez de Prado and co-authors. Neither is exotic. Both are routinely
skipped. Here&rsquo;s what they do, and why I trust them more than any single equity curve.</p>

<h2><span class="sec"><span class="n">§ 00</span> The problem has a name</span>Selection under multiple testing</h2>
<p>Evaluate <span class="m">N</span> configurations of a strategy and report the best one&rsquo;s
Sharpe. Even if <em>every</em> configuration is pure noise with a true Sharpe of zero, the
<em>maximum</em> of <span class="m">N</span> noisy estimates is positive — and grows with
<span class="m">N</span>. Reporting that maximum without accounting for the search is the
quant-finance version of running 20 tests and publishing the one with
<span class="m">p</span>&nbsp;&lt;&nbsp;0.05.</p>
<p>The fix isn&rsquo;t &ldquo;test less.&rdquo; It&rsquo;s to make the search cost <em>explicit</em>
and subtract it back out. That&rsquo;s gate one.</p>

<h2><span class="sec"><span class="n">§ 01</span> Gate one</span>The Deflated Sharpe Ratio</h2>
<p>The Deflated Sharpe Ratio (Bailey &amp; L&oacute;pez de Prado, 2014) asks a sharper question
than &ldquo;is the Sharpe positive?&rdquo; It asks: <strong>given how hard I searched, and given
that my returns are skewed and fat-tailed, what is the probability the true Sharpe exceeds the
benchmark I&rsquo;d expect from luck alone?</strong></p>
<p>For a per-period estimate <span class="m">ŜR</span> over <span class="m">T</span> observations
with skewness <span class="m">&gamma;<sub>3</sub></span> and non-excess kurtosis
<span class="m">&gamma;<sub>4</sub></span>:</p>

<figure class="readout">
  <div class="screen">
    <div class="bar"><span>Equation</span><span class="tag">Deflated Sharpe</span></div>
    <div class="body">
      <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
        <mrow>
          <mi>DSR</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>&#934;</mi>
          <mrow><mo>(</mo>
            <mfrac>
              <mrow>
                <mo>(</mo><mover><mi>SR</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mo>&#8722;</mo>
                <msub><mi>SR</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>)</mo>
                <msqrt><mrow><mi>T</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msqrt>
              </mrow>
              <msqrt>
                <mrow>
                  <mn>1</mn><mo>&#8722;</mo><msub><mi>&#947;</mi><mn>3</mn></msub>
                  <mover><mi>SR</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mo>+</mo>
                  <mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>&#947;</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mn>4</mn></mfrac>
                  <msup><mover><mi>SR</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mn>2</mn></msup>
                </mrow>
              </msqrt>
            </mfrac>
          <mo>)</mo></mrow>
        </mrow>
      </math>
    </div>
  </div>
  <figcaption>EQ. 1 &mdash; the deflated statistic</figcaption>
</figure>

<p>Two things make this more honest than a vanilla Sharpe <span class="m">t</span>-stat. First,
the denominator inflates under negative skew or heavy tails — exactly the regimes where a
na&iuml;ve Sharpe lies. Second, the benchmark <span class="m">SR<sub>0</sub></span> is
<strong>not zero</strong>. It&rsquo;s the <em>expected maximum</em> Sharpe under the null across
<span class="m">N</span> independent trials:</p>

<figure class="readout">
  <div class="screen">
    <div class="bar"><span>Equation</span><span class="tag">Data-snooping benchmark</span></div>
    <div class="body">
      <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
        <mrow>
          <msub><mi>SR</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>=</mo>
          <msqrt><mrow><mi>Var</mi><mo>(</mo><msub><mover><mi>SR</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mi>n</mi></msub><mo>)</mo></mrow></msqrt>
          <mrow><mo>[</mo>
            <mo>(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>&#947;</mi><mo>)</mo>
            <msup><mi>Z</mi><mrow><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup>
            <mrow><mo>(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#8722;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>N</mi></mfrac><mo>)</mo></mrow>
            <mo>+</mo>
            <mi>&#947;</mi>
            <msup><mi>Z</mi><mrow><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup>
            <mrow><mo>(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#8722;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mi>N</mi><mi>e</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>)</mo></mrow>
          <mo>]</mo></mrow>
        </mrow>
      </math>
    </div>
  </div>
  <figcaption>EQ. 2 &mdash; expected max Sharpe under the null; &gamma; is Euler&ndash;Mascheroni</figcaption>
</figure>

<p>That&rsquo;s the whole trick: more configurations &rArr; larger
<span class="m">SR<sub>0</sub></span> &rArr; bigger haircut the winner must overcome. Data-snooping
is priced in rather than wished away. In code, it&rsquo;s a few lines — straight from the
engine&rsquo;s <code class="inl">afml/eval_pbo.py</code>:</p>

<figure class="readout">
  <div class="screen">
    <div class="bar"><span class="tag">afml/eval_pbo.py</span><span>python</span></div>
    <div class="body"><pre><span class="c">_EULER_GAMMA = 0.5772156649015329</span>

<span class="k">def</span> expected_max_sharpe(var_sr, n_trials):
    <span class="c"># SR_0 under the null across n_trials</span>
    <span class="k">if</span> n_trials &lt;= <span class="s">1</span> <span class="k">or</span> var_sr &lt;= <span class="s">0</span>:
        <span class="k">return</span> <span class="s">0.0</span>
    z1 = norm.ppf(<span class="s">1</span> - <span class="s">1</span>/n_trials)
    z2 = norm.ppf(<span class="s">1</span> - <span class="s">1</span>/(n_trials*np.e))
    <span class="k">return</span> np.sqrt(var_sr)*((<span class="s">1</span>-_EULER_GAMMA)*z1 + _EULER_GAMMA*z2)</pre></div>
  </div>
  <figcaption>the benchmark, verbatim from the engine</figcaption>
</figure>

<p>And the DSR itself estimates <span class="m">&gamma;<sub>3</sub>,&nbsp;&gamma;<sub>4</sub></span>
from the realized stream rather than assuming normality:</p>

<figure class="readout">
  <div class="screen">
    <div class="bar"><span class="tag">afml/eval_pbo.py</span><span>python</span></div>
    <div class="body"><pre>sr    = r.mean() / r.std(ddof=<span class="s">1</span>)        <span class="c"># per-period Sharpe</span>
g3    = skew(r)                          <span class="c"># skewness</span>
g4    = kurtosis(r, fisher=<span class="k">False</span>)        <span class="c"># non-excess (normal == 3)</span>

denom = np.sqrt(<span class="s">1</span> - g3*sr + (g4-<span class="s">1</span>)/<span class="s">4</span> * sr**<span class="s">2</span>)
z     = (sr - sr_benchmark) * np.sqrt(T-<span class="s">1</span>) / denom
dsr   = norm.cdf(z)                      <span class="c"># P(true SR &gt; SR_0)</span></pre></div>
  </div>
  <figcaption>the deflated statistic in practice</figcaption>
</figure>

<div class="note">
  <span class="lbl">Promotion threshold</span>
  <p><strong>DSR &gt; 0.95</strong> to size real capital; <strong>&gt; 0.5</strong> to keep a signal
  alive for research. A gorgeous 2.5 Sharpe found across 200 configs routinely deflates below 0.5
  once <span class="m">SR<sub>0</sub></span> is charged against it. That strategy never traded — the
  system working as designed.</p>
</div>

<h2><span class="sec"><span class="n">§ 02</span> Gate two</span>The Probability of Backtest Overfitting</h2>
<p>The DSR polices the <em>magnitude</em> of a winner. PBO (Bailey, Borwein, L&oacute;pez de Prado
&amp; Zhu, 2017) polices the <em>selection procedure itself</em>: if I pick the in-sample best,
does it stay good out-of-sample — or is my ranking no better than a coin?</p>
<p>It&rsquo;s estimated by <strong>Combinatorially-Symmetric Cross-Validation</strong>. Slice the
history (<span class="m">T&times;N</span>, one column per config) into <span class="m">S</span>
contiguous blocks. For every way of splitting them into an in-sample and out-of-sample half —
all <span class="m">C(S,&nbsp;S/2)</span> of them — rank configs IS, take the IS winner, and record
where it lands OOS.</p>

<figure class="readout">
  <div class="screen">
    <div class="bar"><span class="tag">afml/eval_pbo.py · pbo_cscv</span><span>python</span></div>
    <div class="body"><pre><span class="k">for</span> is_sets <span class="k">in</span> combinations(<span class="k">range</span>(n_splits), n_splits//<span class="s">2</span>):
    is_idx  = concat([blocks[i] <span class="k">for</span> i <span class="k">in</span> is_sets])
    oos_idx = concat([blocks[i] <span class="k">for</span> i <span class="k">in</span> rest])

    sr_is  = [sharpe(R[is_idx,  j]) <span class="k">for</span> j <span class="k">in</span> configs]
    sr_oos = [sharpe(R[oos_idx, j]) <span class="k">for</span> j <span class="k">in</span> configs]

    n_star = argmax(sr_is)                    <span class="c"># IS-best config</span>
    omega  = (sr_oos &lt;= sr_oos[n_star]).sum()/(N+<span class="s">1</span>)  <span class="c"># its OOS rank</span>
    logits.append(log(omega/(<span class="s">1</span>-omega)))

pbo = (array(logits) &lt;= <span class="s">0</span>).mean()          <span class="c"># frac below OOS median</span></pre></div>
  </div>
  <figcaption>every partition also evaluated with halves swapped &mdash; no lucky-regime artifact</figcaption>
</figure>

<p>The interpretation is brutal and clean:</p>
<ul class="clean">
  <li><strong>PBO &asymp; 0</strong> — your in-sample ranking genuinely carries out-of-sample. Trust it.</li>
  <li><strong>PBO &asymp; 0.5</strong> — your selection procedure is a random-number generator in a
    lab coat. The IS-best is a coin flip OOS.</li>
</ul>
<p>Note what PBO ignores: the absolute level of returns. A high-Sharpe <em>family</em> can have an
awful PBO — the family is good, but your ability to <em>pick within it</em> is worthless. The two
gates are orthogonal, which is exactly why you want both.</p>

<h2><span class="sec"><span class="n">§ 03</span> Composition</span>How the two gates stack</h2>
<p>Every research iteration runs the same funnel:</p>
<ol class="funnel">
  <li>Build a return matrix — one column per candidate configuration, each column a per-period
    strategy return.</li>
  <li><strong>PBO gate.</strong> Is the <em>selection</em> trustworthy? Near 0.5, stop — no tuning
    saves a procedure that doesn&rsquo;t generalize.</li>
  <li><strong>DSR gate.</strong> For the survivor, is the <em>magnitude</em> real once the search
    cost <span class="m">SR<sub>0</sub></span> is subtracted? Promote only above threshold.</li>
  <li>Only then does the signal reach position sizing (fractional-Kelly, vol targeting) and,
    eventually, live execution.</li>
</ol>
<p>Both gates share one philosophy: <strong>the null hypothesis is that you got lucky, and the
burden of proof is on the strategy.</strong> That inversion is the whole difference between
research that compounds and research that blows up an account on the third leveraged position.</p>

<h2><span class="sec"><span class="n">§ 04</span> Takeaways</span>What to carry out</h2>
<ul class="clean">
  <li>A reported Sharpe is meaningless without the number of configurations behind it. Always
    deflate against <span class="m">SR<sub>0</sub></span>; the haircut grows with your search.</li>
  <li>Skew and kurtosis belong <em>inside</em> the significance test — leverage lives and dies in
    the tails.</li>
  <li>PBO and DSR answer different questions. Run both.</li>
  <li>The healthiest sign in a research log is strategies that die at the gate. Mine kills far more
    than it promotes — which is why the account is still alive.</li>
</ul>

<p class="endnote">Methods from L&oacute;pez de Prado&rsquo;s <em>Advances in Financial Machine
Learning</em> and the associated papers. Implementation snippets are from my own engine; the alpha
signals themselves stay in the vault.</p>
`;
